                "name": "Cameron Van Sant",
                "href": "/profile/Cameron-Van-Sant"
            },
            "answer_text": "I think that\u2019s up to you. You\u2019re using the split attraction model to describe your sexuality as a biromantic homosexual. When the words gay, straight, and later, bisexual were first applied to sexuality, they predated the split attraction model quite a bit, so they don\u2019t quite line up easily. The fact is that allosexual people who don\u2019t have split attractions are going to usually interpret bisexual as biromantic bisexual. Here you have a few options: Identify as bisexual anyway if you feel like you\u2019re \u201cclose enough\u201d/if you\u2019re in a situation where you\u2019d prefer not to explain your sexuality/romantic attractionIdentify as bisexual if you feel like you belong in the larger bisexual community with diverse romantic orientations and sexualities (and are okay with people misinterpreting that sometimes)You could also do what some people I know do, and identify as queer to simplify things down.If none of those seem like a good match, feel free to continue identifying as biromantic homosexual. I would just like to throw this out there: Your romantic attraction to women is valid. I\u2019m sure there are people out there who will love to eyeroll at you and say \u201cOkay, but you\u2019re really gay\u201d or whatever. You don\u2019t have to do anything with women or have any kind of relationships for your attraction to be validated. It is just inherently valid. ",
