            "author_info": {
                "name": "Dan Holliday",
                "href": "/profile/Dan-Holliday"
            },
            "answer_text": "You can be anything you are; you can identify as anything you like. Stop worrying about labels. I'm not saying this because I'm one of those whack-jobs that thinks that labels are evil. I'm saying this because words are clunky and they create barriers and motivations to fit your life into terms that you can communicate to others (seriously, who doesn't want to be well-understood by their circle of associates?). Because of this, you will end up artificially adjusting your behavior simply to make yourself easier to define and explain.  First be yourself. Stop worrying about the labels. After you have found your identity then we can sit down and explain the nuances of who you are. But we will do that casually and intellectually. When we have a dispassionate conversion that is free of guilt or expectations then we will achieve understanding of who you are. But that can never happen until you walk away from fitting in to clunky words that never truly define your innate value as a human being. ",
